Type 1: (aka T1R, RR - 'reversal reaction')
  • Type 1 lepra reactions typically affect the skin and nerves, and there are no systemic symptoms. The reaction is classified as mild or severe.
  • There is no neutrophil leukocytosis of elevation of CRP.
    • Pain or tenderness of nerves AND even loss of nerve function. (type 2 doesn't affect nerves). (most affected are ulnar, sciatic, external popliteal, facial, and cervical nerves)
    • Can cause irreversible nerve damage (foot drop!) within 24 hours; prompt treatment with steroids prevents this.
  • Sudden eruption of numerous painful nodules. (Lesions are mainly on extensory aspect of limbs and the face) associated with fever and fatigue.
  • There is high WBC and high CRP.
  • Pregnancy, lactation and puberty are risk factors. Source
  • Type 2 lepra reactions have become rare since the introduction of clofazimine treatment. (Start clofazimine if not already started if Type 2 reaction occurs)
  • Systemic involvement +
    • tender lymphadenopathy
    • Renal impairment -> can be severe
    • Liver failure -> can be severe
  • Treatment: Corticosteroids, thalidomide or methotrexate. Clofazimine is NOT useful in acute Type 2 lepra reaction.

    Clofazimine causes a copper (red and dark skin and hair) pigmentation, particularly on areas exposed to light starting during the first 10 weeks of treatment. This is reversible but takes several months. Also causes icthyosis.

[!INFO] Overview of thrombophilia
Predisposition to thrombosis:

  • Heritable thrombophilias, acquired thrombophilias, Haemolytic anaemias (+?others)
    Heritable thrombophilias
  1. Factor V Leiden - gain of coagulant function
  2. Protein C deficiency - loss of anticoagulant function
  3. protein S deficiency - loss of anticoagulant function
  4. Antithrombin deficiency

Acquired thrombophilias

  1. Antiphospholipid syndrome is an acquired thrombophilia.

Haemolytic anaemias can predispose to thrombosis, particularly

  1. [[Cytopaenias#Paroxysmal nocturnal haemoglobinuria|PNH]]
  2. Thalassemia
  3. Sickle cell anaemia
  4. Haemolysis in general.
  5. There can be mulitple mechanisms Source
- 30-50% of SLE patients have antiphopholipid  antibodies.

  • These antibodies bind to their corresponding plasma proteins when the proteins bind to membrane phospholipids (?which probably induces a conformational change) Source

*Don't read this bit: It's Confusing ;)

However, aPL is also directed against a variety of other antigenic targets such as prothrombin (PT), phosphatidylserine/prothrombin (PS/PT) complexes, vimentin/cardiolipin complexes, annexin A2, lupus anticoagulant and annexin A5
They appear to have anticoagulant activity because they prolong APTT.

  • DRVVT test - very sensitive to lupus anticoagulant effect.

  • Normally, the LOS remains closed between swallows because of intrinsic properties of it's muscles.

  • Transient lower oesophageal sphincter relaxations occur during swallowing (TLESRs) to allow food to pass.

  • The frequency of TLESRs increases in patients with GORD allowing gastric contents to reflux.

  • Any residual reflux is cleared by secondary peristalsis, salivary bicarbonate, and gravity.
    An "Acid pocket" of acid not neutralized by incoming food and fluid can serve as a reservoir of 'refluxable' acid. This can be targeted with an antacid-alginate combination.

  • Treatment is initiated on clinical diagnosis.

However, Endcoscopy is indicated in

  • refractory cases or
  • those with red flag symptoms (dysphagia, weight loss, bleeding) or
  • for patients with longstanding reflux (10 years) as they have a high risk of [[2020-NOV-BasicSciences#Barrett oesophagus|Barrett's Oesophagus]]
  • Demonstration of oesophagitis or Barrett's oesophagus on endoscopy confirms GORD.

"Upper endoscopy is not required to make a diagnosis of GERD. However, upper endoscopy can detect esophageal manifestations of GERD (eg, Barretts metaplasia, erosive esophagitis) and can rule out an upper gastrointestinal tract malignancy"

Endoscopy is sensitive for oesophagitis but it will miss nonerosive reflux disease. (NERD)

  • Symptoms are 'often' functional or due to hypersensitive oesophagus.

  • The most sensitive test -> 24 ambulatory pH monitoring. (used to assess the cause when symptoms are refractory)

  • Oesophgeal manometry is done to exclude motility disorder in patients with chest pain and normal upper GI endoscopy
    The DeMeester score is a composite of pH and manometry (?and other) and if 14.72, indicates presence of reflux.

  1. Alginate containing antacids - 10ml tds - most common treatment. Forms a gel raft which prevents reflux.
  2. PPIs - 4 weeks course of once daily PPI resolves symptoms in 60%.
    1. The role of prokinetics is limited due to lack of data Source
    2. Domperidone, cisapride, mosapride (cisapride and mosapride can cause arrhythmias)
  3. invasive

Dog tape worm

  • A 2-7mm long small tape form whose definitive host is the dog.
  • Intermediate host is animals like sheep.
  • Sheep tissues have cysts which are infective when ingested by a dog.
  • The adult forms in the dog then shed eggs with faeces which are usually ingested by the sheep, but can also be ingested by humans.
  • One ingested, the eggs hatch the the larvae penetrate the intestinal wall and take up residence in the tissues.
  • In the tissues, they from hydatid cysts.
  • The cysts usually grow for many years and are asymptomatic until they cause symptoms due to pressure effects.
  • However, if a cyst ruptures, it can cause analphylaxis, or a milder fever, and dissemination of the parasites within.
  • Treatment: Surgery or less invasive procedures like PAIR (percutaneous aspiration, injection of chemicals and reaspiration).
